# What is an Interface?

An interface defines a contract: it lists method signatures that any implementing class must provide. Interfaces cannot contain properties (except constants) and all methods are public by default.

```php
interface Logger {
    public function log($message);
}

class FileLogger implements Logger {
    public function log($message) {
        file_put_contents('log.txt', $message . PHP_EOL, FILE_APPEND);
    }
}
```

A class can implement multiple interfaces.

# Polymorphism in Action

Polymorphism means "many forms". With interfaces, you can write code that works with any class that implements a given interface, regardless of its specific type.

```php
function processLogger(Logger $logger) {
    $logger->log("Processing...");
}

$logger = new FileLogger();
processLogger($logger); // works with any Logger
```

```php
<?php
interface PaymentGateway {
    public function charge($amount);
}

class StripeGateway implements PaymentGateway {
    public function charge($amount) {
        echo "Charging $$amount via Stripe.";
    }
}

class PayPalGateway implements PaymentGateway {
    public function charge($amount) {
        echo "Charging $$amount via PayPal.";
    }
}

function checkout(PaymentGateway $gateway, $amount) {
    $gateway->charge($amount);
}

$stripe = new StripeGateway();
checkout($stripe, 100);

$paypal = new PayPalGateway();
checkout($paypal, 200);
?>
```
